<subSubSection id="39FDFA134BBFF093607E3235A98CD31F" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" type="notes">
<paragraph id="FD04719BDE54B5A9F2FCAE6D787510C1" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C9ABC25C660A2DD8BBFAB2B8C97E5CFB" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
The new species should be a member of 
<taxonomicName id="7B3DAC9683D810454E7C47A401C9DCDB" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia subsp. sect." order="Cucurbitales" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Leprosae" species="lanceolata" subSpecies="sect.">Begonia sect. Leprosae</taxonomicName>
Y.M. Shui according to its clavate berry fruit (
<bibRefCitation id="D47D66930C6C539F9C844EF0A618B877" author="Shui, Y-M" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Bulletin of Academia Sinica" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" pagination="313 - 327" refId="B22" refString="Shui, Y-M, Peng, CI, Wu, CY, 2002. Synopsis of the Chinese species of Begonia (Begoniaceae), with a reappraisal of sectional delimitation. Botanical Bulletin of Academia Sinica 43: 313 - 327" title="Synopsis of the Chinese species of Begonia (Begoniaceae), with a reappraisal of sectional delimitation." volume="43" year="2002">Shui et al. 2002</bibRefCitation>
). In the section, it is more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="112C9B65A2548A5768A530C23CB3005D" genus="B." lsidName="B. longicarpa" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" rank="species" species="longicarpa">
<emphasis id="375F07039F95DB917E713468FEF1F1AE" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">B. longicarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A306B85B389330A77D19002C8D288570" genus="B." lsidName="B. leprosa" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" rank="species" species="leprosa">
<emphasis id="2081116B0A0E5B8BAFEC277A15807D48" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">B. leprosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hance than the other species. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="8703E8E5DCB4DF1C1297CFFCE13D89E9" genus="B." lsidName="B. longicarpa" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" rank="species" species="longicarpa">
<emphasis id="4BB87F56C8720001D3FE65C34357797E" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">B. longicarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the habitat of ground soil and different mainly in the petal number (5 
<emphasis id="70A14F90306386673BDB0B6267D4C0D9" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
3), the hairs of petiole (hispid 
<emphasis id="0A0F5BBB8EADFEAA0EC101ABB1D3E670" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
pubescent) and the morphology of the segments of placentation per locule (irregular placenta segments vs. 2 regular placenta segments per locule). It is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="B35A491DA7C8E72367EC20CCDBE54656" genus="B." lsidName="B. leprosa" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" rank="species" species="leprosa">
<emphasis id="EBECF70CEBC2B64F820BA79337CBE1FD" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">B. leprosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the morphology of the fruit and hairs on the petiole, but differs mainly in the habitat (ground soil 
<emphasis id="5B979DB883B5B206432CEC1F8D472711" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
limestone surface), the abaxial surface of leaves (obviously reticulate nerves 
<emphasis id="AE678618ACD1DAE718FEFDDCD316E204" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
obscurely reticulate nerves) and the petal number of the female (5 
<emphasis id="A0BC4AF4113204E6774ECE77923FFA16" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
4) and the morphology of placentation at the upper part of ovary (axile 
<emphasis id="71353664685D91C4B394FF39F9DEC41C" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
parieta). As to the white spots on the adaxial leaf surface, it is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName id="72B4EDEF14F76EBA58133C0FA00C9A73" authorityName="S. H. Huang &amp; Y. M. Shui" authorityYear="1994" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia gulinqingensis" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gulinqingensis">
<emphasis id="4E47661378E9AA0D10B091BF08A2E50D" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Begonia gulinqingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
S.H.Huang &amp; Y.M.Shui in 
<taxonomicName id="59EA3539C681432C66540EA5812AFAAC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia subsp. sect." order="Cucurbitales" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Diploclinium" species="gulinqingensis" subSpecies="sect.">Begonia sect. Diploclinium</taxonomicName>
, but different in the fruit (berry 
<emphasis id="9D7B32C1837F8A7B58BC57752F861989" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">vs.</emphasis>
capsule) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CDF2DAA940AB2EE31574DEC6E5B85AD9" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Begonia erectocarpa H. Q. Nguyen, Y. M. Shui &amp; W. H. Chen A Habitat B Stipule, dorsal view and face view C View of adaxial leaf D Close-up of adaxial leaf E View of abaxial leaf F Close-up of abaxial leaf G Inflorescence H Staminate flower, face view, side view and dorsal view I Pistillate flower, face view, side view and dorsal view J Fruits K Young fruit L Serial cross sections of ovary. (A, C, E, H, I, J, K photographs by S. W. Guo; B, D, F, G and L by H. Q. Nguyen)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.94.23248.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/182236" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">4</figureCitation>
-J; 
<bibRefCitation id="F31D64387D6B117636B4C6E5165811AF" author="Shui, Y-M" journalOrPublisher="Yunnan Science and Technology Press, Kunming" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" refId="B21" refString="Shui, Y-M, Chen, W-H, 2017. Begonia of China. Yunnan Science and Technology Press, Kunming" title="Begonia of China." year="2017">Shui and Chen 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
